// Semantic direction:
// tui_app is the top-level application struct; it holds app_state_tui and orchestrates the event loop.
// app_init runs once at startup; app_update processes one tui_event and returns new app_state_tui.
// app_render draws the entire UI into a tui_frame given the current app_state_tui.
// app_quit_key is the global keybinding that exits the event loop (often 'q' or Ctrl+C).
// app_help_bar renders the current keybindings at the bottom of the screen.
// screen is one full-screen view; screen_stack enables navigation history (push/pop/replace).
// push_screen adds a new screen on top; pop_screen returns to the previous one.
// component is a reusable sub-widget with its own state and event handling.
// focus_ring manages which component is active; focus_next_c/prev_c advance with Tab/Shift-Tab.
// keybinding associates a key_code with an action and a description for the help bar.
// binding_global means the keybinding is active in any screen context.
// keymap_match checks if a key_event matches any registered keybinding and returns the action.
// keymap_help produces a sorted list of bindings for the current context.
// command_palette is a fuzzy-searchable list of all registered actions (Ctrl+P in editors).
// palette_run executes the selected action directly.
// notification is a transient message displayed for notif_duration milliseconds.
// notif_queue renders one notification at a time; the next is shown when the current expires.
// modal is a blocking overlay; it captures focus until the user confirms or cancels.
// pane splits the screen into independently scrollable regions.
// pane_split divides the active_pane horizontally or vertically; pane_resize adjusts the split ratio.
// pane_focus_t moves keyboard focus to a different pane.

// Primitive flow:
// app event loop: event -> app_handle_event(state, event) -> new_state
//   keymap_match(event) -> action -> action_execute(state, action) -> new_state
//   push_screen: stack.push(new_screen) -> re-render
//   pop_screen: stack.pop() -> re-render previous
//   modal open: modal_open(content) -> captures focus -> on key: confirm/cancel -> modal_close
//   notification: notif_queue.push(msg, duration) -> render top-right -> dismiss after duration
// command palette: Ctrl+P -> palette_open -> type query -> palette_filtered -> Enter -> palette_run

// This defines the TUI application framework: screen stacks, component focus,
// keybindings, command palette, notifications, modals, and split panes.
